The paper deals with combinatorial auctions for the secondary spectrum market, which involves assigning channels to multiple bidders while ensuring low interference. This involves modeling interference conflicts using a conflict graph, which is a graph-theoretic concept. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) and Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. The paper also proposes a novel LP formulation for the problem, which involves optimization and algorithms, making the paper relevant to the Information Theory (cs.IT) and Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses incentive-compatible mechanisms for the auction, which involves designing mechanisms for rational agents, making the paper relevant to the Computational Economics and Social Choice (cs.CE) sub-category.
